<br>
I am a level 23 troll warrior twink with decent equiptment and have most skills maxed for my level.<br>
The reason for the powerleveling would be to help fill in the classes that are needed for further advancement of the guild.<br>
<br>
Thanks for any info<br>
<br>
Bogg  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uadexxeda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adex Xeda</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://kilroyc.globalhelix.com/adex_icon.jpg height=30 width=30 BORDER=0></span><br> <b>The Swift</BR>Steel Warrior Contributor</b><br>  Posts: 173<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/8/01 7:45:29 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://kilroyc.globalhelix.com/adex_portrait.jpg width = 136 height = 267 ></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_sword.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The pro's and con's of powerleveling</span><hr size=1> Some of the most fun I ever had was in mid level camps such as the Avatar of Fear area in Cazic Thule, or the royals area in Sol B.<br>
<br>
If you PL right through those levels you miss out on the fun they provide.<br>
<br>
If your guild needs a warrior quick I can understand your motiviation, but be aware that you miss out on some fun times when you PL.<br>
<br>
 <p><center><IMG SRC="http://kilroyc.globalhelix.com/adex_nametag.jpg"></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ushikariiapoccalypse.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shikarii Apoccalypse</A></span><br> <b>is a Formidable Opponent</b><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/8/01 7:48:39 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re:</span><hr size=1> more than likely end up being a PL'd level <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> whatever</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> warrior who has shitty defensive and offensive skills<br>
<br>
if it's what ya want have fun, if you can keep up your skills and actually <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> learn</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the class it will be even better for you and your guild. more than likely though you'll be a big pile of hit points that can't swing a sword or take a hit<br>
<br>
there's more to being a meat shield than just standing there getting your teeth knocked down your throat, i would advise you to learn the class and progress naturally and make your mistakes now; making them later on will only make it worse to correct.<br>
<br>
but that's just my 2 bits <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uboggbasher.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Boggbasher</A></span><br> <b>knows that Warriors are Superior</b><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/8/01 7:56:21 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>    Re: The pro's and con's of powerleveling</span><hr size=1> How about this:<br>
<br>
Powerlevel up to level 40, use the two hell levels to regain any skills that fall behind and continue to learn the skills of being a warrior.<br>
<br>
<br>
What ya think?<br>
<br>
Bogg <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ushikariiapoccalypse.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shikarii Apoccalypse</A></span><br> <b>is a Formidable Opponent</b><br>  Posts: 142<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/8/01 8:11:55 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Re: The pro's and con's of powerleveling</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showMessage?topicID=464.topic">pub14.ezboard.com/ftheste...=464.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
i suggest reading it. take it from there.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/unavilus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Navilus</A></span><br> <b>knows that Warriors are Superior</b><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/8/01 9:10:39 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Re: The pro's and con's of powerleveling</span><hr size=1> I suggest just playing through it.  If you need to be a higher level fast, then just work on xp and don't worry about trade skills and quests and things like that.  I went to Kunark at 27 with my warrior and about a month and a half later I am now 44.  That is regular playing and I do have a job  so only part-time playing.  Warriors level fast anyway... I think it is the one class that doesn't need powerleveling to shoot through the levels.  My guild is concerned not in getting me to higher levels but because I am going up TOO fast, and won't have anyone in guild to group with!  LOL<br>
<br>
Navilus the Dashing<br>
44 dwarf warrior<br>
Tunare <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ukazarksnaketongue.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kazark Snaketongue</A></span><br> <b>is a Formidable Opponent</b><br>  Posts: 104<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/8/01 10:05:19 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Re: The pro's and con's of powerleveling</span><hr size=1> If you know how to play the class and done the leveling before you played this character go for it.  Skills can keep up.  I soloed to 51 in 11 days played and only lacked in 2 HB, mainly because I didn't have a decent 2 HB weapon.  All skills keep up and you'll be fine.  The only thing I hate is people who powerlevel or powergame that don't take the time to learn to play right.  I call those people gimps and you see way too many players like that these days.  All up to you though.  At the time I chose to retire my shaman there was only one 50 + warrior.  I was getting bored at the time and retired my 52+ Iksar Shaman.  I leveled fast for my guild and became the best in guild.  Now because of our reputation we have quite a few 55+ warriors and are starting to get to that uber guild status.  If your guild needs warriors and you want to play one go for it.<br>
<br>
Kazark Snaketongue, 60 Iksar Warlord<br>
 Member of Arcis on Povar   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uyildabodacious.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yilda Bodacious</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/ez_icons/emoticons/laugh.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <b>knows that Warriors are Superior</b><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#FF0000>(5/8/01 8:16:09 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:  Re: The pro's and con's of powerleveling</span><hr size=1> I dont suggest powerleveling if its your first character.  Learn the game mechanics, etc before hand and save a lot of people grief.  I already had a 54 druid, 46 necro and over 90 days played on the druid alone before I made a warrior.<br>
<br>
